    overview: "Blotting techniques are transfer and detection methods used to identify specific DNA (Southern), RNA (Northern), or protein (Western) molecules. Named after Edwin Southern who invented the DNA blot. These foundational techniques are increasingly replaced by PCR and sequencing but remain important conceptually and for certain applications like HIV confirmatory testing (Western blot, now largely replaced).",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Southern blot (DNA): DNA → restriction enzyme digestion → agarose gel electrophoresis (separates by size) → transfer (blot) to nitrocellulose/nylon membrane → hybridize with labeled DNA probe → detect specific DNA sequence. Northern blot (RNA): intact RNA → electrophoresis → transfer → hybridize with labeled probe → detect specific mRNA (gene expression analysis). Western blot (protein): protein → SDS-PAGE electrophoresis (separates by molecular weight) → transfer to membrane → detect with antibody (primary Ab + labeled secondary Ab or enzyme-conjugated Ab).",
    clinicalRelevance: "Southern blot applications: gene rearrangement studies (TCR, IgH for lymphoma clonality), RFLP analysis, fragile X trinucleotide repeat expansion sizing. Western blot: HIV confirmatory testing (historically—now replaced by HIV-1/2 differentiation immunoassay in most algorithms), Lyme disease confirmatory testing. Northern blot: research/gene expression (largely replaced by RT-qPCR and RNA-seq).",
