    overview: "FISH uses fluorescently labeled DNA probes to detect specific DNA sequences on chromosomes, interphase nuclei, or tissue sections. It bridges conventional cytogenetics and molecular testing by providing spatial/chromosomal context. FISH can be performed on dividing and non-dividing cells (interphase FISH), unlike conventional karyotyping which requires metaphase spreads.",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Principle: complementary fluorescent DNA probe hybridizes to target DNA sequence on specimen (chromosome spread, interphase nuclei, tissue section). Probe is denatured (single-stranded) and applied to denatured specimen DNA → hybridization at complementary sequence → wash unbound probe → visualize with fluorescence microscopy. Probe types: (1) Locus-specific: binds specific gene region (e.g., BCR-ABL fusion). (2) Centromeric/alpha satellite: binds repetitive centromere sequences (chromosome enumeration—detect trisomy, monosomy). (3) Whole chromosome paint: labels entire chromosome (detects translocations). (4) Break-apart probes: two colors flanking a breakpoint—separate signals indicate translocation.",
    clinicalRelevance: "Clinical applications: BCR-ABL fusion in CML/ALL (dual-fusion or dual-color probe), HER2 amplification in breast cancer (gene copy number determines trastuzumab eligibility), ALK rearrangement in NSCLC (crizotinib eligibility), trisomy 13/18/21 and sex chromosome aneuploidies (prenatal diagnosis), del(5q)/del(7q)/del(17p) in MDS/AML, PML-RARA in APL, MYC rearrangement in Burkitt lymphoma.",
    signsSymptoms: "FISH is a laboratory technique used for diagnostic and prognostic purposes.",
