    examPitfalls: ["CMA does NOT detect balanced translocations or inversions—still need karyotype if balanced rearrangement is suspected", "CMA has higher resolution than karyotype but CANNOT replace it for all indications", "VUS are a significant challenge with CMA—parental testing helps determine if a CNV is inherited (likely benign) or de novo (more likely pathogenic)"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "CMA vs karyotype?", answer: "CMA: detects small CNVs (50-100 kb resolution), no cell culture needed, faster turnaround, higher diagnostic yield. Cannot detect balanced rearrangements. Karyotype: detects balanced translocations/inversions, structural rearrangements, all aneuploidies, but lower resolution (5-10 Mb), requires cell culture, lower diagnostic yield for submicroscopic changes. They are complementary." }, { question: "What is uniparental disomy?", answer: "UPD occurs when both copies of a chromosome (or chromosome segment) come from one parent, with no contribution from the other. SNP arrays detect this as long contiguous stretches of homozygosity. UPD is clinically significant when it involves imprinted regions (Prader-Willi: paternal deletion or maternal UPD of 15q11; Angelman: maternal deletion or paternal UPD of 15q11)." }]
