    faqJson: [{ question: "What is dimorphism?", answer: "Dimorphic fungi exist in two forms depending on temperature. At 25°C (environmental temperature): MOLD form with hyphae and conidia. At 37°C (body temperature): YEAST form (or spherule for Coccidioides). Dimorphic fungi include: Histoplasma, Blastomyces, Coccidioides, Sporothrix, Talaromyces (Penicillium) marneffei. Mnemonic: 'Mold in the Cold, Yeast in the Heat.'" }, { question: "Why is the Ohio/Mississippi River Valley significant?", answer: "Histoplasma thrives in soil enriched with bird (especially starling) and bat droppings, which provide nitrogen. The Ohio and Mississippi River Valleys have warm, humid conditions ideal for fungal growth. Activities that disturb contaminated soil (demolition, cave exploration, farming) generate aerosols of microconidia causing outbreaks." }]
